:{"1385–1425":"1385–1425","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1386–1426":"1386–1426","1379–Male":"1379–Deceased","1400–1488":"1400–1488","1415–1498":"1415–1498","1370–1396":"1370–1396","1364–1398":"1364–1398","February 1396":"February 1396","1385":"1385","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1488":"1488","1498":"1498","1398":"1398","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","East Hoathly, Sussex, England":"East Hoathly, Sussex, England","Norbury, England, United Kingdom":"Norbury near Malpas, Marbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Barrington, Somerset, England":"Barrington, Somerset, England","Norbury, Cheshire, England":"Norbury, Cheshire, England","Abingdon, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Abingdon, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire, Cheshire and Lancashire): habitational name, primarily from Tatton in Cheshire, but occasionally from Tatton in Chickerell (Dorset). The placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Tāta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Taton","meanings":["English (west Yorkshire): variant of   Tatton  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Isabel Tatton was born in 1385, in Staffordshire, England, her father, Robert de Tatton, was 15 and her mother, Margaret De Hyde, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with John Barrington. She died in 1425, in Barrington, Somerset, England, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1385–1425":"1385–1425","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1386–1426